'''''Lunar Lander''''' is a 1980 video game published by [[Adventure International]].

==Gameplay==
''Lunar Lander'' is a game in which the player must land a ship on the Moon, in the style of other ''[[Lunar Lander (video game genre)|Lunar Lander]]'' games.<ref name="CGW4"/>

This game was part of a series of arcade game [[video game clone|clones]] for the [[TRS-80]] and [[Atari 8-bit computers]]. Though not exactly the same as the [[Atari, Inc.]] version of ''[[Lunar Lander (1979 video game)|Lunar Lander]]'', it was advertised as "an arcade game simulation".<ref name="Adventure1">{{cite magazine |magazine=Adventure International Microcomputer Software Catalog |title=Lunar Lander |volume=3 |issue=2 |page=12 |date=1983 |publisher=[[Adventure International]] |url=http://chiclassiccomp.org/docs/content/computing/ScottAdams/ScottAdams_AdventureInternational_3-2.pdf}}</ref><ref name="Adventure2">[https://books.google.com/books?id=jtInDwAAQBAJ&dq=%22Lunar+Lander%22+%22adventure+international%22&pg=PT90 ''The A-Z of Atari 8-bit Games'', p. 83]</ref>

==Reception==
Richard McGrath reviewed the game for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'', and stated that "I have no real complaints. Adventure International has a winning program here. It is just as advertised--a quality version of an old standby."<ref name="CGW4">{{cite magazine |last=McGrath |first=Richard |title=The Eagle Has Landed |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=May–June 1982 |volume=1 |issue=4 |pages=34–35}}</ref>

